				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Buffett Picks His &#8216;Bear&#8217; for Annual Meeting</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Peter Lattman			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2013-03-04T16:54:33+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">March 4, 2013 11:54 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">March 4, 2013 11:54 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w592"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/03/05/business/Buffett/Buffett-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002099786" width="592" height="428" alt="Douglas Kass, the founder of hedge fund Seabreeze Partners Management." /><span class="credit">John Van Beekum for The New York Times</span><span class="caption">Douglas Kass, the founder of hedge fund Seabreeze Partners Management.</span></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/b/warren_e_buffett/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Warren E. Buffett.">Warren E. Buffett</a> has found his bear.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In his annual letter to shareholders, published on Friday, Mr. Buffett said that he wanted to âspice things upâ by finding a money manager with an unfavorable view of <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=BRK.A&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Berkshire Hathaway Inc">Berkshire Hathaway</a> to participate in the companyâs annual meeting.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe only requirement is that you be an investment professional and negative on Berkshire,â he wrote.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Monday, Mr. Buffett said Douglas A. Kass, a hedge fund manager who has shorted Berkshire stock and thus bet that its price will fall, would be added to the panel of analysts at the companyâs yearly gathering on May 4. He will be among those who question Mr. Buffett and Berkshireâs vice chairman, Charles T. Munger, on stage, when more than 18,000 devotees are expected to descend on Omaha for the three-day meeting, often described as the Woodstock for capitalists.</p>
<div class="entry entry-related"><h4>Related Links</h4>	<div class="entry-related">
		<ul>
					<li><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2013/03/01/buffett%E2%80%99s-annual-letter-plays-up-newspapers%E2%80%99-value/">In His Annual Letter, Buffett Plays Up Newspapers (March 1, 2013)</a></li>
				</ul>
	</div>
	</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Kass, the owner of Seabreeze Partners Management in Palm Beach, Fla., is a well-known stock picker by virtue of his writings for a financial Web site, <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=TST&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about TheStreet Inc">TheStreet</a>, and frequent appearances on CNBC.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI am going to <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/d/disneyland/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Disneyland">Disneyland</a> â I mean, Omaha!â Mr. Kass, 63, wrote on Monday. âI will be Daniel in the Lionâs Den, wading in a sea of Warren Buffettâs strongest admirers.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Buffett, famous for his swift decision-making when it comes to closing deals and buying stocks, wasted no time in picking his âBerkshire bear.â But also credit Mr. Kass for taking the bull by the horns, so to speak.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Kass said he had read the Berkshire letter as soon as it came out on Friday, just as he had done each of the last 40 years. After seeing Mr. Buffettâs solicitation, he began preparing a proposal. Mr. Kass has credentials as a Berkshire bear, having <a href="//www.thestreet.com/story/10406915/1/kass-katch-11-reasons-to-short-berkshire.html">written a piece</a> in March 2008 for TheStreet, âKass Katch: 11 Reasons to Short Berkshire,â that laid out his rationale for betting against the company. (Berkshireâs stock is up about 16 percent since Mr. Kass wrote the column, but it did have down years in 2008 and 2011).</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI have worshiped at the altar of Warren Buffett since the late 1970s,â Mr. Kass wrote. âIndeed my writings over the last seven years have often been punctuated with Buffett-isms.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Yet Mr. Kass said that despite his idolatry of Mr. Buffett, 82, the Berkshire business faced a number of headwinds. He cited Mr. Buffettâs advanced age, explaining that âthere will never be another Warren Buffett.â He also said that Berkshireâs large size could impede returns, pointing out that even Mr. Buffett had written that the companyâs asset base was too large to make outsize gains in the future. Both criticisms are even more potent today than they were a half-decade ago.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While Berkshireâs book value â Mr. Buffettâs preferred performance metric â has soundly outperformed the broader stock market over its 48-year history, the Standard &#038; Poorâs 500-stock index has outperformed Berkshire in three of the last four years and five of the last 10.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Saturday, while watching the Kansas-West Virginia college basketball game, Mr. Kass completed his application. He included his bearish article on Berkshire from TheStreet, as well as a presentation he gave last year at a value-investing conference, in which he advocated shorting the United States bond market.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He also included his rÃ©sumÃ©, which highlighted that he began his career as a housing analyst at the investment bank Kidder Peabody and later worked for the billionaire investor Leon Cooperman, who runs the hedge fund Omega Advisors.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Kass, who said he had never met Mr. Buffett, also supplied him with a list of references of other prominent investors who know Mr. Buffett, including Howard Marks, the chairman of Oaktree Capital Management, and Mario Gabelli, the chief of <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=GBL&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Gamco Investors Inc">Gamco Investors</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Monday morning, in a live CNBC interview, Mr. Buffett made the surprise announcement that he had selected Mr. Kass.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThink of tough questions,â Mr. Buffett challenged Mr. Kass on the air. âSee if you can drive the stock down 10 percent.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Kass was in his Palm Beach office, preparing for the trading day with CNBC playing in the background, and he heard Mr. Buffett make the announcement.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI was as shocked as everyone else,â said Mr. Kass, who grew up in Rockville Centre, N.Y., on Long Island. âI am flattered, honored and surprised.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He will join two Berkshire bulls, the insurance analyst Cliff Gallant of Nomura Securities and Jonathan Brandt of the money management firm Ruane, Cunniff &#038; Goldfarb, on stage at the CenturyLink Center in Omaha in two months.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And even though Mr. Kass will be the stick in the mud at the celebratory weekend event, he acknowledges that deep down, he remains an unabashed fan of Mr. Buffett.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI canât wait to take a picture with him,â Mr. Kass said.</p>
